Norm Mineta, a son of California, dedicated his life to public service and fought for civil liberties after experiencing the injustice of internment. He served in the U.S. Army and as the Mayor of San Jose, where he recognized the importance of infrastructure in connecting people to economic opportunities. Throughout his ten terms in Congress and as a Cabinet Secretary, Mineta tirelessly fought for resources for his community. He also played a crucial role in laying the foundation for Asian American leaders nationwide, co-founding the Asian Pacific American Institute for Congressional Studies and the Congressional Asian Pacific American Caucus. He will be remembered for his leadership during challenging times and his commitment to making America a better place. The author expresses gratitude for Mineta's legacy and offers condolences to his family.